70
00:04:08,947 --> 00:04:13,768
And he learnt this when he was working in advertising when no one wants to read your

71
00:04:13,768 --> 00:04:14,949
stuff.

72
00:04:14,949 --> 00:04:20,011
And he explains that once you start with the idea that nobody automatically wants to read

73
00:04:20,011 --> 00:04:23,212
your shit, that you develop empathy.

74
00:04:23,212 --> 00:04:25,973
You ask yourself, why don't they want to read it?

75
00:04:25,973 --> 00:04:27,673
Why don't they want to play my game?

76
00:04:28,810 --> 00:04:32,393
And with this, quote here, you acquire the skill

77
00:04:32,393 --> 00:04:35,875
that is indispensable to all artists and entrepreneurs.

78
00:04:35,875 --> 00:04:38,237
That the ability to switch back and forth

79
00:04:38,237 --> 00:04:40,619
between your imagination from your own point of view

80
00:04:40,619 --> 00:04:43,821
as a writer developer to the point of view of your player.

81
00:04:43,821 --> 00:04:46,363
You're thinking about what the player is thinking

82
00:04:46,363 --> 00:04:48,124
and experiencing at each point.

83
00:04:48,124 --> 00:04:51,567
And this approach is behind successful projects

84
00:04:51,567 --> 00:04:52,928
in all art forms.

85
00:04:52,928 --> 00:04:56,290
So let's have a look at how you can action this

86
00:04:56,290 --> 00:04:57,911
and how this relates to franchises.

87
00:05:00,080 --> 00:05:05,704
Here we have, in Hollywood, there is a technique called the sequence approach,

88
00:05:05,704 --> 00:05:08,365
which some of you will be familiar with here.

89
00:05:08,365 --> 00:05:12,068
It was developed by Frank Daniel, who, after analyzing hundreds

90
00:05:12,068 --> 00:05:16,291
of successful screenplays, realized it was an emerging best practice

91
00:05:16,291 --> 00:05:19,233
that would help us all make great screenplays.

92
00:05:19,233 --> 00:05:22,095
Frank was a screenwriter himself, a playwright, a novelist,

93
00:05:22,095 --> 00:05:25,798
had a master's degree in music, and a doctorate in film.

94
00:05:26,238 --> 00:05:29,461
And he influenced generations of filmmakers in his role

95
00:05:29,461 --> 00:05:31,923
as the director of the Australian Film Institute,

96
00:05:31,923 --> 00:05:35,165
sorry, the American Film Institute,

97
00:05:35,165 --> 00:05:38,148
as well as he was head of film at USC,

98
00:05:38,148 --> 00:05:40,770
as well as Columbia, and he was artistic director

99
00:05:40,770 --> 00:05:42,752
of Robert Redford's Sundance Institute,

100
00:05:42,752 --> 00:05:44,873
the first artistic director.

101
00:05:44,873 --> 00:05:48,256
And interestingly for us, his sequence approach focuses

102
00:05:48,256 --> 00:05:50,498
on how the audience will experience the story

103
00:05:50,498 --> 00:05:53,460
and what the writer can do to make that experience better.

104
00:05:54,321 --> 00:05:56,903
So just quickly, what is the sequence approach?

105
00:05:56,903 --> 00:06:01,007
So basically, what it does is it take the existing structure

106
00:06:01,007 --> 00:06:03,008
that we all use, and you can see here

107
00:06:03,008 --> 00:06:05,010
with the beginning, middle, and end,

108
00:06:05,010 --> 00:06:06,711
and adds shorter sequences.

109
00:06:07,474 --> 00:06:10,378
But the emphasis here is not on the shorter sequences,

110
00:06:10,378 --> 00:06:14,843
but that these sequences are driven by an audience question.

111
00:06:14,843 --> 00:06:17,126
The crucial point to this approach

112
00:06:17,126 --> 00:06:20,770
is to think about what drives the audience interest

113
00:06:20,770 --> 00:06:21,911
at each point in your film.

114
00:06:21,911 --> 00:06:23,814
What questions drive them?

115
00:06:23,814 --> 00:06:25,115
What are they thinking about?

116
00:06:25,776 --> 00:06:32,400
And so you are the one then that designs that interest with a ticking clock, with dramatic irony,

117
00:06:32,400 --> 00:06:37,042
which is when we know more than the characters know, and importantly with dramatic tension,

118
00:06:37,042 --> 00:06:42,986
when we are withholding an anticipated resolution. Now this thinking about the audience experience,

119
00:06:42,986 --> 00:06:48,128
what is in their mind, and what they know right now, and what they're expecting next,

120
00:06:48,128 --> 00:06:50,270
is common to all successful works.

121
00:06:52,372 --> 00:06:55,513
So for example, Brian Upton, who is the co-founder of Red

122
00:06:55,513 --> 00:06:58,754
Storm Entertainment, where he designed the original Rainbow

123
00:06:58,754 --> 00:07:01,675
6 and Ghost Recon, and was senior game designer at Sony,

124
00:07:01,675 --> 00:07:05,996
he talks about situational design, where the nexus of

125
00:07:05,996 --> 00:07:07,937
play is not in the transactions.

126
00:07:07,937 --> 00:07:10,258
It's not in the actions.

127
00:07:10,258 --> 00:07:11,518
It's not in the interface.

128
00:07:11,518 --> 00:07:15,019
The nexus of play is in the player's mind.

129
00:07:15,019 --> 00:07:17,400
And he talks about the importance of designing for

130
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:18,720
player anticipation.

131
00:07:19,920 --> 00:07:21,521
Okay, so how does this actually work in a game?

132
00:07:21,521 --> 00:07:25,683
Let's have a look at what remains of Edith Finch.

133
00:07:25,683 --> 00:07:29,926
So, our first question is one that seems that it would drive us right to the end of the game,

134
00:07:29,926 --> 00:07:33,888
and that is, what remains of Edith Finch?

135
00:07:33,888 --> 00:07:37,330
Like, what does that actually mean?

136
00:07:38,177 --> 00:07:42,160
And then, when we actually are going through the beginning of the play,

137
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:44,941
we find another one that comes in very early,

138
00:07:44,941 --> 00:07:47,103
and that is, how do I get to the house?

139
00:07:47,103 --> 00:07:50,565
The designers have strategically placed a house in the distance,

140
00:07:50,565 --> 00:07:53,187
a weenie, as we know,

141
00:07:53,187 --> 00:07:56,769
to get us to think about where we are to go and what we are to do.

142
00:07:58,340 --> 00:08:00,961
And then they mention that we have a key.

143
00:08:00,961 --> 00:08:03,462
So the developers have us thinking,

144
00:08:03,462 --> 00:08:05,042
what does this key open?

145
00:08:05,042 --> 00:08:08,544
I need to find something that needs this key.

146
00:08:08,544 --> 00:08:11,585
You see how these questions also work as objectives.

147
00:08:11,585 --> 00:08:15,847
We have a writing approach, a design approach,

148
00:08:15,847 --> 00:08:17,087
all operating together.

149
00:08:18,252 --> 00:08:22,197
And then, if we've had these previous small questions

150
00:08:22,197 --> 00:08:25,241
answered to our satisfaction, then it

151
00:08:25,241 --> 00:08:28,445
is more likely that the players will actually

152
00:08:28,445 --> 00:08:30,988
continue through to the rest of the game.

153
00:08:30,988 --> 00:08:31,168
In fact.

154
00:08:31,958 --> 00:08:35,800
Brandon Sanderson, a best-selling science fiction and fantasy writer,

155
00:08:35,800 --> 00:08:38,121
talks about this technique as a promise.

156
00:08:38,121 --> 00:08:41,783
He doesn't see it as a question, but as an open bracket and a closed bracket.

157
00:08:41,783 --> 00:08:45,444
You promise that something will happen, and then you follow it through.

158
00:08:45,444 --> 00:08:49,326
You indicate to the reader that your story will be about something,

159
00:08:49,326 --> 00:08:50,467
and then you deliver on it.

160
00:08:51,487 --> 00:08:54,869
Now, you all know this in terms of genre.

161
00:08:54,869 --> 00:09:00,352
You know that if you promise a player that it's a party game, it's a first-person shooter,

162
00:09:00,352 --> 00:09:04,754
it's an open-world game, it's a horror, it's a comedy, whatever it is, you actually have

163
00:09:04,754 --> 00:09:07,295
to deliver on the expectations of those genres.

164
00:09:07,295 --> 00:09:14,199
It's a feedback loop where our players engage in a continuous reappraisal, and these promises

165
00:09:14,199 --> 00:09:18,021
are one factor in how they decide and why we must deliver.

166
00:09:19,475 --> 00:09:24,560
I really like the notion of a promise because it's about what the players are thinking about.

167
00:09:24,560 --> 00:09:31,226
It's also what we're signaling, what we will provide, and also with the word promise, it

168
00:09:31,226 --> 00:09:34,029
implies that we have a responsibility to honour it.

169
00:09:39,016 --> 00:09:41,798
Okay, so how can we use this for our shit franchise?

